	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Jeroen wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">This is some interesting input. Seems alot of people on here stay up late!<br />(btw I heard those work times in japan are really brutal, how is it?)</div>
<br />
<br />Japan is a workaholic culture in general. This mean even thought the government set some rules about overtime and a normal work week is supposed to be 40h, company often expect you do to 2h of "compulsory" overtime (and they try to make sure the government doesn't know about it.  Then you have those people that arrive at 9h in the morning and leave at 23h at night.  Some people are forced to do so (my wife when working at the bank in the past was working 15h per day and sometime weekend too! that's slavery) or some people seems to see that at the norm or even enjoy it.  It's is common to hear about people dying out of overwork　（残業殺し zangyogorshi, which mean death by overwork if my memory is good). And overtime is in most of the time not paid at all or in my case "after you do more than 40h during the month" (...)
<br />
<br />As for myself, I decided not to enter in that crazy cycle and just do my normal hours.  I'm lucky that I can do that.  But still, it is common to have between an 1h or 2 of commute to go to work so it makes the day longer. Imagine the guy that worked already 15h and now have to 1h30 of train.. This mean 18h of his day was for work only.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


